description: From Middle English tethen, from Old English tēþan (“to teethe”), from Proto-Germanic *tanþijaną (“to teethe”), from Proto-Germanic *tanþs (“tooth”). Cognate with German zähnen (“to provide with teeth”).

verbs.description: teethe (third-person singular simple present teethes, present participle teething, simple past and past participle teethed)

examples: Babies typically start teething at about six months.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To bite on something to relieve discomfort caused by growing teeth.
examples: She'll teethe on anything that she can get into her mouth.
